{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:14:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:14:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16471"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16471"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65414"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9162"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50853"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1646"},{"type":"tags","id":"2443"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21757"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65414"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of worsening headache and confusion. She has a medical history of bacterial meningitis diagnosed three weeks ago, treated with intravenous antibiotics. She takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears drowsy with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 13 (E3, V4, M6). Her pulse rate is 65/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. She has papilloedema on fundoscopy. CT brain shows dilated ventricles with periventricular lucency.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of cerebral oedema is most likely present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cytotoxic oedema","Vasogenic oedema","Interstitial oedema","Ionic oedema","Osmotic oedema"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of raised intracranial pressure secondary to post-meningitis hydrocephalus. The CT findings of dilated ventricles with periventricular lucency are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Einterstitial oedema\u003C/strong\u003E, which occurs when cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) accumulates in the periventricular white matter due to increased intraventricular pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytotoxic oedema\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to cellular swelling from failure of ATP-dependent ion pumps, typically seen in early cerebral ischaemia. This is not the primary mechanism in hydrocephalus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasogenic oedema\u003C/strong\u003E results from blood-brain barrier disruption allowing protein-rich fluid to enter the extracellular space. While this can occur in meningitis, it is not the cause of the periventricular changes seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIonic oedema\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to disruption of cellular ionic gradients but without cell death. This is not a primary feature of hydrocephalus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsmotic oedema\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is an osmotic gradient drawing water into brain tissue, such as in hyponatraemia. This is not relevant to the pathophysiology presented here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn hydrocephalus, increased intraventricular pressure forces CSF across the ependymal lining of the ventricles into the surrounding white matter. This transependymal flow creates the characteristic periventricular lucency seen on CT, representing interstitial oedema. This process contributes to the clinical features of raised intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Interstitial cerebral oedema occurs when cerebrospinal fluid accumulates in the periventricular white matter due to increased intraventricular pressure.","Hydrocephalus leads to interstitial oedema through transependymal flow of CSF across the ventricular wall.","Increased intracranial pressure can result from the combination of hydrocephalus and interstitial oedema."],"references":["Jha RM, Kochanek PM, Simard JM. Pathophysiology and treatment of cerebral edema in traumatic brain injury. Neuropharmacology. 2019 Feb;145(Pt B):230-246. doi: 10.1016/j.neuropharm.2018.08.004. Epub 2018 Aug 4. PMID: 30086289; PMCID: PMC6309515.","Jha SK. Cerebral Edema and its Management. Med J Armed Forces India. 2003 Oct;59(4):326-31. doi: 10.1016/S0377-1237(03)80147-8. Epub 2011 Jul 21. PMID: 27407555; PMCID: PMC4923559.","Cook AM, Morgan Jones G, Hawryluk GWJ, Mailloux P, McLaughlin D, Papangelou A, Samuel S, Tokumaru S, Venkatasubramanian C, Zacko C, Zimmermann LL, Hirsch K, Shutter L. Guidelines for the Acute Treatment of Cerebral Edema in Neurocritical Care Patients. Neurocrit Care. 2020 Jun;32(3):647-666. doi: 10.1007/s12028-020-00959-7. PMID: 32227294; PMCID: PMC7272487.","Halstead MR, Geocadin RG. The Medical Management of Cerebral Edema: Past, Present, and Future Therapies. Neurotherapeutics. 2019 Oct;16(4):1133-1148. doi: 10.1007/s13311-019-00779-4. PMID: 31512062; PMCID: PMC6985348."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50853"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16471"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50853"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T13:26:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T11:21:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9162"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65414"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (ident